Mayor John Dal Broi said the most recent development with the proposed school options involved officials from the Department of Education who supported the $45 million super school.

“Griffith is one of the regional areas growing above the state average and education and health are two aspects attracting people to the area so I would expect to see what was previously put in place to continue,” he said.

Cr Dal Broi said he would seek a meeting with the new minister if proposed options changed. 

Despite being replaced by Rob Stokes, Mr Piccoli supported his successor and said it was a privilege to have served as Minister of Education for nearly six years.

&quot;In 165 years there have only been four Ministers of Education who served longer than I have and there is a lot of goodwill towards what I have achieved as minister, which gives me a great personal satisfaction,&quot; Mr Piccoli said.

“I can look back over my time as Minister satisfied with what I have achieved.

&quot;What more could you want.”

